Halm accordingly supposes that, although the trial was originally meant to extend over five days, ‘for some unexplained reason,' the proceedings were curtailed, the aequatio palorum being taken on the third day. He does not however notice that, if so, either the trial did not begin on the fourth, or else it ended before the eighth of April.

It is now generally recognized that the supposed discrepancy in Asconius rests upon a mistranslation. When he says quarta dz'e . . . adesse elaberentur he means ‘they were ordered to be present on the fourth day,' not ‘on the fourth day they ware ordered to be present‚’ ie. next day. (It is usual, and probably right, to cut out in daim posterum as an addition. The passage can, however, be construed in this sense with them, since in legal language such pleonasms are not uncommon.) · For the construction of the passage I refer to my note.
